This is a silly result about a "physically wrong" scaling limit of neural nets.

Claim (informalmost). Finite bit precision overparametrized NNbayes has good generalization properties. 

Claim (informal). Finite bit precision overparametrized NNbayes learns functions with small circuits quickly.

Claim (less informal). Assume finite bit precision of weights, and that weights are bounded. Consider NNbayes learning on an MLP of depth d and width N, in the "strong prior" limit, ie where you just always have nearly full probability on the smallest L^2 norm fit compatible with the data so far. Let C(f) denote the width of the smallest neural net that implements the function f:R^d->R. Then when doing in-distribution learning of f, at any width N>C(f), NNbayes very likely gets >99.9% test accuracy after seeing poly(C(f),d) train data points.

Remark. the constant inside the poly(C(f),d) depends on the inverse of the bit precision eps and the max weight size

Remark. again, this is a trivial braindead result

the argument is just:
* if the function has a small circuit, then there is this finite L^2 norm construction where you just use a subset of the neurons to implement the circuit and set everything else to 0. the squared L^2 norm of this is poly(complexity)
* how many functions with smaller NN implementations are there? well, since there is a weight quantum eps, we can just bound the number of nonzero weights by the L^2 norm times 1/eps^2, so that's still poly(complexity)
* but how many circuits are there with only poly(complexity) edges? only exp(poly(complexity)). like, there are many more implementations, but only at most this many different "lower occam complexity" functions.
* use a union bound to see that by seeing poly(complexity) data points, all the smaller functions which have <99.9% accuracy get ruled out with exponentially high probability 
* so occam learning indeed whp leaves you with a function with >99.9% test accuracy
